I Mean...
text:
I mean... Has anyone else noticed how many people now start their sentences with, "I mean..."?

Though it's not a holey new phenomenon, it does seem to be one that's relatively recent. I'm noticing it all. The. Time. I even hear radio broadcasters say it once in a while. It's common in business meetings across generations (I interact with a lot of Gen X and Millennials). People will even post comments, starting a sentence with "I mean...".

It doesn't even seem to be used in a way that makes any sense sometimes (see the first line of this post).

Am I just hyper sensitive to it, or is it something that's become a linguistic cultural phenomenon people have become accustomed to, similar to people saying "...um..." in the middle of sentences?

What DO you mean?! What does "I mean..." mean?

Who said it first? How did it catch on? Why has it spread so fast?

It's both slightly annoying to me, but more amazing that it's just everywhere! Though, I haven't noticed people older than GenX saying it, I don't think.

I mean... it's like... uh... like... crazy!
